s New Labour Governments forced through a major conceptual shift for social enterprise, co-operative and third sector activity. Many structures, formed as community responses to massive deindustrialisation in the 1970s and 1980s, were repositioned to bid against the private sector to obtain contracts for delivery of low cost public services. Based on previously unseen archival materials and interviews with key players between 1998 and 2002, when major social enterprise and third sector policy changes occurred, Huckfield offers an alternative narrative of social enterprise in the UK, showing how local communities have been denied the restoration of local economic and social democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCooperative societieszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aCooperative societieszGreat BritainxHistoryy21st century. 0aSocial entrepreneurshipzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial entrepreneurshipzGreat BritainxHistoryy21st century. 4aPolitical Studies 2021. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh  aantecedents.  acooperatives.  adeindustrialisation.  amarketisation.  aprocurement.  apublic service.  asocial economy.  asocial enterprise.  athird sector.  avoluntary and community.1 aHuckfield, Leslie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614974940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526149749423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526149749/original  a978-3-11-128198-8  Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles